\@writefile{lof}{\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {1}{\ignorespaces \textbf  {Floor Theorem and the Information Bound of Bounded Cognition.} (\textbf  {A})~Smallest knowable error $S_{\flat }$ on a log $y$-axis ($10^{-2}$ to $10^{2}$) versus cognitive capacity $|K|$ on a log $x$-axis ($2$ to $4096$) across twelve receivers connected by a line. The floor decreases monotonically by half a decade per doubling of $|K|$, from $S_{\flat }=50.00$ at $|K|=2$ down to $S_{\flat }=0.0244$ at $|K|=4096$, but remains strictly positive at every tested capacity. This is the empirical signature of Theorem~\ref {thm:floor-positivity} (Floor Positivity): $S_{\flat }(\mathcal  {R})>0$ for every bounded $\mathcal  {R}$, with the floor a receiver-intrinsic property fixed by the discretisation. No external choice of candidate or truth can change the floor; only enlarging $|K_{\mathcal  {R}}|$ does. (\textbf  {B})~Heatmap of the information content $I_{\epsilon }=\log _{2}((100-S_{\flat })/\epsilon )$ on a $5\times 4$ grid spanning $S_{\flat }\in [10^{-3},10]$ and $\epsilon \in [10^{-3},1]$ (axes in $\log _{10}$), viridis colourmap encoding bit count from $\sim 6.6$ at the worst $(S_{\flat }=10,\epsilon =1)$ corner to $\sim 16.7$ at the best $(S_{\flat }=10^{-3},\epsilon =10^{-3})$ corner. The bilinear structure of the bound in $(\log S_{\flat },\log \epsilon )$ is the predicted form of Theorem~\ref {thm:info-bound}; measured values at every grid point match prediction to machine precision (max absolute error $0.00\times 10^{0}$ over 20 pairs). (\textbf  {C})~Three-dimensional surface of $I_{\epsilon }$ over the $(\log _{10}\epsilon ,\log _{10}S_{\flat })$ plane, viridis colourmap, viewing angle elevation $24^{\circ }$ azimuth $-60^{\circ }$. The surface is the bilinear $\log _{2}((100-S_{\flat })/\epsilon )$ of Theorem~\ref {thm:info-bound}: information content is monotone increasing in both $\log (1/S_{\flat })$ and $\log (1/\epsilon )$, with no interaction term, and the gradient is unit-slope in each direction. Information cost diverges only along the joint zero limit $S_{\flat }\to 0,\epsilon \to 0$. (\textbf  {D})~Floor measurements from twelve capacities (navy markers) compared against the analytic prediction $S_{\flat }=100/|K|$ (coral dashed line) on a semi-log $x$-axis. The receiver-intrinsic floor saturates the prediction across four decades of capacity. The plot operationalises the dual relationship between cognitive capacity and resolution: a receiver wishing to distinguish at precision $\epsilon $ must support $|K|\geq 100/\epsilon $ knowledge states.}}{5}{figure.caption.3}\protected@file@percent }
\providecommand*\caption@xref[2]{\@setref\relax\@undefined{#1}}
\newlabel{fig:panel-floor-bounded}{{1}{5}{\textbf {Floor Theorem and the Information Bound of Bounded Cognition.} (\textbf {A})~Smallest knowable error $\Sfloor $ on a log $y$-axis ($10^{-2}$ to $10^{2}$) versus cognitive capacity $|K|$ on a log $x$-axis ($2$ to $4096$) across twelve receivers connected by a line. The floor decreases monotonically by half a decade per doubling of $|K|$, from $\Sfloor =50.00$ at $|K|=2$ down to $\Sfloor =0.0244$ at $|K|=4096$, but remains strictly positive at every tested capacity. This is the empirical signature of Theorem~\ref {thm:floor-positivity} (Floor Positivity): $\Sfloor (\receiver )>0$ for every bounded $\receiver $, with the floor a receiver-intrinsic property fixed by the discretisation. No external choice of candidate or truth can change the floor; only enlarging $|K_{\receiver }|$ does. (\textbf {B})~Heatmap of the information content $I_{\epsilon }=\log _{2}((100-\Sfloor )/\epsilon )$ on a $5\times 4$ grid spanning $\Sfloor \in [10^{-3},10]$ and $\epsilon \in [10^{-3},1]$ (axes in $\log _{10}$), viridis colourmap encoding bit count from $\sim 6.6$ at the worst $(\Sfloor =10,\epsilon =1)$ corner to $\sim 16.7$ at the best $(\Sfloor =10^{-3},\epsilon =10^{-3})$ corner. The bilinear structure of the bound in $(\log \Sfloor ,\log \epsilon )$ is the predicted form of Theorem~\ref {thm:info-bound}; measured values at every grid point match prediction to machine precision (max absolute error $0.00\times 10^{0}$ over 20 pairs). (\textbf {C})~Three-dimensional surface of $I_{\epsilon }$ over the $(\log _{10}\epsilon ,\log _{10}\Sfloor )$ plane, viridis colourmap, viewing angle elevation $24^{\circ }$ azimuth $-60^{\circ }$. The surface is the bilinear $\log _{2}((100-\Sfloor )/\epsilon )$ of Theorem~\ref {thm:info-bound}: information content is monotone increasing in both $\log (1/\Sfloor )$ and $\log (1/\epsilon )$, with no interaction term, and the gradient is unit-slope in each direction. Information cost diverges only along the joint zero limit $\Sfloor \to 0,\epsilon \to 0$. (\textbf {D})~Floor measurements from twelve capacities (navy markers) compared against the analytic prediction $\Sfloor =100/|K|$ (coral dashed line) on a semi-log $x$-axis. The receiver-intrinsic floor saturates the prediction across four decades of capacity. The plot operationalises the dual relationship between cognitive capacity and resolution: a receiver wishing to distinguish at precision $\epsilon $ must support $|K|\geq 100/\epsilon $ knowledge states}{figure.caption.3}{}}
